# Project initialization (forks from this starter kit)

When the user has not yet personalized a copy of this monorepo, help them before building features.

## When to skip entirely (canonical template repo)

**Do not** prompt for or run project initialization if this checkout is the **maintained template** (same GitHub repository as documented in root [`package.json`](package.json) **`repository.url`**):

- Normalize `git remote get-url origin` and **`repository.url`** (compare `host` + `pathname`, allow `.git` suffix drift). If they refer to the **same** repo, you are on the canonical template checkout—**skip** `project-init` unless the user explicitly asks to rename or template something.

## When initialization applies

If **both** are true:

1. Root [`package.json`](package.json) still has **`"name": "cloudflare-multiworker-template"`** (the default template package name).
2. `origin` is missing **or** normalized `origin` does **not** match normalized **`repository.url`** (e.g. the user forked or uses a different remote).

Then the project is likely an **uncustomized fork**. Inform the user once per session (or when they ask to deploy or ship) that they should personalize **`PRODUCT_PREFIX`**, root `name` / `repository`, README, and UI copy so deploys and docs match their app. Offer to walk through it using the **project-init** skill: [`../skills/project-init/SKILL.md`](../skills/project-init/SKILL.md).

Do not block unrelated tasks if the user declines; they may be iterating locally.

## After initialization

Once the root `package.json` **`name`** is no longer **`cloudflare-multiworker-template`**, or **`repository.url`** matches their fork and they have set **`PRODUCT_PREFIX`**, treat the repo as personalized unless the user asks again.
